<div1 type="segment" n="A">
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.a1" type="proverb" n="19.a1"><p id="t6119.p1" n="1-5" corresp="c6119.A.19.a1.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.10" from="t.6.1.10.10">6.1.10.10-12</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.17" from="t.6.1.17.b3">6.1.17.b3</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.17">ll. 14-17</xref>, <xref doc="t.5.6.7">5.6.7: ll. 29-31</xref></note>
My black mountain has sprouted white gypsum. My mother sent to me a man from the forest, who has given me paralysed hands. My mongoose, which used to eat strong-smelling food, can no longer stretch its neck even towards a jar of ghee.
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="B">
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b1" type="proverb" n="19.b1"><p id="t6119.p2" n="1" corresp="c6119.B.19.b1.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.09" from="t.6.1.09.a12">6.1.09.a12</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.21" from="t.6.1.21.b4">6.1.21.b4</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.2">6.1.24.2</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: YBC 4677 ll. 1-2</xref></note>
When a fattened pig is about to be slaughtered, one says: <q>Let me replace what I eat.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b2" type="proverb" n="19.b2"><p id="t6119.p3" n="2-3" corresp="c6119.B.19.b2.2">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.09" from="t.6.1.09.a13">6.1.09.a13</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.21" from="t.6.1.21.b5">6.1.21.b5</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.2">6.1.24.2</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: YBC 4677 ll. 3-4</xref></note>
As the piglet snuffles around, it says: <q>I can no longer take pleasure in eating.</q></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b3" type="proverb" n="19.b3"><p id="t6119.p4" n="4-5" corresp="c6119.B.19.b3.4">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.137">6.1.02.137</xref></note>
Build like a lord -- live like a slave! Build like a slave -- live like a lord!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b4" type="proverb" n="19.b4"><p id="t6119.p5" n="6-7" corresp="c6119.B.19.b4.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.02" from="t.6.1.02.135">6.1.02.135</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.3">6.1.24.3</xref></note>
He who destroys houses destroys silver. He who destroys a house destroys gold.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b5" type="proverb" n="19.b5"><p id="t6119.p6" n="8-9" corresp="c6119.B.19.b5.8">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.09" from="t.6.1.09.a14">6.1.09.a14</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.4">6.1.24.4</xref></note>
The lord's wife kneels, the slave girl dies. The lord kneels, the slave dies.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b6" type="proverb" n="19.b6"><p id="t6119.p7" n="10-12" corresp="c6119.B.19.b6.10">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.71">6.1.03.71</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.11" from="t.6.1.11.19">6.1.11.19</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.5">6.1.24.5</xref></note>
<gap extent="1 line unclear"/>
&X;&X; its hands at the edge of the desert &X;&X;
<gap extent="1 line fragmentary"/></p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.b7" type="proverb" n="19.b7"><p id="t6119.p8" n="13-15" corresp="c6119.B.19.b7.13">
&X;&X; you should know &X;&X;
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/>
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="C">
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c1" type="proverb" n="19.c1"><p id="t6119.p9" n="1-2" corresp="c6119.C.19.c1.1">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.25">6.1.03.25</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.5">6.2.5: YBC 4677 ll. 8-10</xref></note>
What did <w type="DN">Enlil</w> make? Chaff! The lance struck. It went into the flesh.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c2" type="proverb" n="19.c2"><p id="t6119.p10" n="3" corresp="c6119.C.19.c2.3">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.03" from="t.6.1.03.26">6.1.03.26</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.9">6.1.24.9</xref></note>
When the sun is setting outside so that you cannot even recognise the hand in front of you, go inside!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c3" type="proverb" n="19.c3"><p id="t6119.p11" n="4-5" corresp="c6119.C.19.c3.4">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.145">6.1.01.145</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: ll. 87-88</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.28" from="t.6.1.28.4">6.1.28.4</xref></note>
Accept your lot and make your mother happy! Run fast and make your god happy!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c4" type="proverb" n="19.c4"><p id="t6119.p12" n="6" corresp="c6119.C.19.c4.6">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.146">6.1.01.146</xref></note>
Marry the wife of your choice.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c5" type="proverb" n="19.c5"><p id="t6119.p13" n="7-9" corresp="c6119.C.19.c5.7">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.147">6.1.01.147</xref></note>
May <w type="DN">Inana</w> make a hot-limbed wife lie with you! May she bestow upon you broad-shouldered sons! May she find for you a place of happiness!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c6" type="proverb" n="19.c6"><p id="t6119.p14" n="10-11" corresp="c6119.C.19.c6.10">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.126">6.1.01.126</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.14" from="t.6.1.14.42">6.1.14.42</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.22">6.1.22: l. 34</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.3" from="t623.h8">6.2.3: UET 6/2 284</xref></note>
A plant as sweet as a husband, a plant as sweet as a mother: may <w type="DN">Ezina-Kusu</w> <note lang="eng">the grain goddess</note> dwell in your home.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c7" type="proverb" n="19.c7"><p id="t6119.p15" n="12-14" corresp="c6119.C.19.c7.12">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.21" from="t.6.1.21.c1">6.1.21.c1</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.23" from="t.6.1.23.18">6.1.23.18</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.1.24" from="t.6.1.24.8">6.1.24.8</xref></note>
A man's waterskin is his life. A man's sandals are his eyes. A man's wife is his supervisor (?). A man's son is his protective shade. A man's daughter is his eager servant (?). A man's daughter-in-law is his policeman.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c8" type="proverb" n="19.c8"><p id="t6119.p16" n="15" corresp="c6119.C.19.c8.15">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.21" from="t.6.1.21.c2">6.1.21.c2</xref></note>
A daughter's fianc&eacute; &X;&X;.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.c9" type="proverb" n="19.c9"><p id="t6119.p17" n="16" corresp="c6119.C.19.c9.16">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.190">6.1.01.190</xref></note>
Fatty meat is good and so is fatty mutton.
<gap extent="unknown no. of lines missing"/></p>
</lg></div1><div1 type="segment" n="D">
<lg id="t.6.1.19.d1" type="proverb" n="19.d1"><p id="t6119.p18" n="1-2" corresp="c6119.D.19.d1.1">
<gap extent="2 lines fragmentary"/></p></lg>
