<lg id="t.6.1.19.f2" type="proverb" n="19.f2"><p id="t6119.p34" n="2" corresp="c6119.F.19.f2.2">
A great river is a grave.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.f3" type="proverb" n="19.f3"><p id="t6119.p35" n="3-4" corresp="c6119.F.19.f3.3">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.15" from="t.6.1.15.a9">6.1.15.a9</xref></note>
From the horizon to the very heart of the heavens, the bread is too little for his great stomach! The grain from every hand in his Land is too little for him!</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.f4" type="proverb" n="19.f4"><p id="t6119.p36" n="5-7" corresp="c6119.F.19.f4.5">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.40">6.1.01.40</xref>, <xref doc="t.6.2.1">6.2.1: Ni 4469 Seg. A ll. 1-4</xref></note>
Let &X;&X; be &X;&X;. Let his bread be &X;&X; foul food; no man should eat it.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.f5" type="proverb" n="19.f5"><p id="t6119.p37" n="8" corresp="c6119.F.19.f5.8">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.58">6.1.01.58</xref></note>
Morsels of bread and tasty onions are the food of the school (?).</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.f6" type="proverb" n="19.f6"><p id="t6119.p38" n="9" corresp="c6119.F.19.f6.9">
<note lang="eng">cf. <xref doc="t.6.1.01" from="t.6.1.01.48">6.1.01.48</xref></note>
In the fields, coarse flour is meat fat.</p></lg>
<lg id="t.6.1.19.f7" type="proverb" n="19.f7"><p id="t6119.p39" n="10" corresp="c6119.F.19.f7.10">
